04705nam a22008295i 9780813598956DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2019006067  a97808135989567 a10.36019/97808135989562doi  a(DE-B1597)537496  a(OCoLC)1120698258  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aU310b.E24 2020 7aPER0000002bisacsh1 aEagle, Jonna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar Games /cJonna Eagle. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aQuick Takes: Movies and Popular Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Live -- t2. Onscreen -- t3. Interactive -- tAcknowledgments -- tFurther Reading -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe word “wargames” might seem like a contradiction in terms. After all, the declaration “This is war” is meant to signal that things have turned deadly serious, that there is no more playing around. Yet the practices of war are intimately entangled with practices of gaming, from military videogames to live battle reenactments. How do these forms of play impact how both soldiers and civilians perceive acts of war? This Quick Take considers how various war games and simulations shape the ways we imagine war. Paradoxically, these games grant us a sense of mastery and control as we strategize and scrutinize the enemy, yet also allow us the thrilling sense of being immersed in the carnage and chaos of battle. But as simulations of war become more integrated into both popular culture and military practice, how do they shape our apprehension of the traumatic realities of warfare? Covering everything from chess to football, from Saving Private Ryan to American Sniper, and from Call of Duty to drone interfaces, War Games is an essential guide for anyone seeking to understand the militarization of American culture, offering a compact yet comprehensive look at how we play with images of war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aComputer war games. 0aMass media and warxHistory. 0aWar films. 0aWar games. 0aWar in mass mediaxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2019z9783110605785oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishz978311061001708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069033040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081359895640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813598956423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813598956.jpg  a978-3-11-061001-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-069033-0  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-073823-0  Art and Architecture eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2019  aZDB-23-DPKb2019